 <!-- ============= Introduction ============================== -->
  <sect1 id="intro">
    <title>Introduction</title>

    <para>
     <application>&app; Version &version;</application> 
     </para>
    <para>&app; is an Email Client,  for the  Gnome and GTK environments. Written for users of all levels  <application> &app; </application>
    is designed to be fast, simply configured,  lightweight and functional.
    </para>
    <note> <para>
      To run <application>&app;</application>, select
       
	<guisubmenu>Internet </guisubmenu>
	<guimenuitem>&app;</guimenuitem>
        
      from the <guimenu>Main Menu</guimenu>, or type 
      <application>cronos</application> on the command line.
  	</para></note>
	<para>
       This Help-Manual &manver; describes 
      <application>&app;</application> Version &version;
    </para>
   
    <para>Refer to <xref linkend="install"> for Installation instructions.</para>
     <para>Refer to <xref linkend="configuration"> for post install configuration.</para>
  </sect1>


 <!-- INSTALLATION -->
 
   <sect1 id="install">
    <title>Installing &app;</title>
    <para>
      <application>&app;</application>  Is built using the <application>GNU Autoconf and Automake </application>Tools and friends.
       Intergration with Gnome is fairly comprehensive.
       </para>
       <para>
      You may also run this application under a "pure" GTK environment without Gnome. 
      </para>
      <para>
      This should enable &app; to be installed anywhere the GIMP Tool Kit is available including 
      ports of GTK to the <trademark> Windows </trademark>  Operating System.
      </para>
      <important>
      <para>
      To build and run &app;&version; you need to have the following libraries installed:
      </para>
      <para>
      (my apologies to <trademark>Windows</trademark> Users  I'm not sure what they need beyond GTK)
      </para>
      <para>Please let me know so that I can update this manual. <email>&pete;</email> 
      or see <xref linkend="authors">
      </para>
      <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
      <para>
       <programlisting> glib-config --version</programlisting>
      glib-1.2.8 or later
      </para>
       </listitem>
       <listitem>
       <para>
      <programlisting>gtk-config --version</programlisting>
      gtk-1.2.8 or later
      </para>
     </listitem>
      <listitem>
      <para>
       <programlisting> gnome-config --version</programlisting>
       To use with GNOME  your working gnome libs will need to be fairly recent
       <application>gnome-libs 1.2.5</application>  are on this system (and all is well), earlier versions may well work.
      </para>
       </listitem>
       <listitem>
      <para>
      To use the Gnome Print Utility you will need <application> libgnomeprint.so.11.2.4</application> or later wherever you have 
      your Gnome libraries installed. For Example:
      </para>
      <para>
      <programlisting>ls /usr/lib/libgnomeprint.*</programlisting> or
      <programlisting>ls /usr/local/lib/libgnomeprint.*</programlisting>
      </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
      <para>
      You will of course have to have the usual<application> GNU </application>tools on hand as well. 
      </para>
      <para>
     <emphasis> Though if you have a working GNU / LINUX  (or BSD?) system (with GTK onboard) all should be more than just fine.</emphasis>
      </para>
      </listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
      </important>

		 
       <sect2 id="installing">
       <title>Installation</title>
      <para>
      <application>&app;</application> may arrived packaged in a number of formats.
      </para>
      
      <para>The most likely are shown here:</para>
      <orderedlist>
      <listitem><para>Gzipped Source Tarballs</para>
      <para>These look like this<application> &app;.&version;.tar.gz</application>
      </para>
      <para>See <xref linkend="gzipped"> for install instructions.
      </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
      <para>Bzip2 Tarballs</para>
      <para> This is less likely at the moment, however they will usually look like this:</para>
      <para>
     <application> &app;&version;.tar.bz2 </application>
     </para>
     <para>See <link linkend="bzipped">  Bzipped </link>
      for install instructions.
      </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
      <para>Finally &app; is available as a <application>Redhat Package Manager - Package.</application></para>
      <para>These RPM's should look like this:</para>
      <para><application>&app;&version;.ixxx.rpm</application></para>
      <para> Instructions for these are at<link linkend="rpms"> Red Hat Packages</link></para>
      </listitem>
      </orderedlist>
    <note>
    <para>
    If you are installing from tar balls please read the README  and INSTALL files (at least)
     in the source. These are likely to be more up to date than this manual.
    </para>
    <para> Other formats are possible not least of which are zip and debs.
   Support for these or other formats may be added should the demand for them warrant it.
   </para>
   </note>
     
   <sect3 id="gzipped">
   <title>GNU Zipped Source Packages</title>
   <subtitle>gzip</subtitle>
   <para>These are the most common method of distributing application packages (and other stuff ) in the UNIX / LINUX world.  </para>
   <para>To install &app; from the same directory as the package :</para>
   <orderedlist>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user@ X]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> tar zxvf &app;&version;.tar.gz</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user@ X]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting>cd &app;&version;</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user @ &app;&version] #</emphasis>
   <programlisting> ./configure</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user @&app;&version;] #</emphasis>
   <programlisting> ./make</programlisting></para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem><para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;] #</emphasis>
   <programlisting>su</programlisting></para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem><para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;] #</emphasis><programlisting> password: your-root-password</programlisting>
   </para></listitem>
   <listitem><para><emphasis>[root @&app;&version;] #</emphasis><programlisting> ./make install</programlisting>
   </para></listitem>
   <listitem><para><emphasis>[root @&app;&version;] #</emphasis><programlisting> exit</programlisting>
   </para></listitem>
   <listitem><para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;] #</emphasis><programlisting> cronos</programlisting>
   </para></listitem>
   </orderedlist>
   <note><para>The text between<quote> [ and ] </quote>is a representation of  your terminal prompt. 
   Yours will  be different to that shown and may change markedly when you <application>"su" </application>to root.</para></note>
   <para>For further instruction and options for using<application> configure</application> and 
   <application>make </application>commands please see the documentation in the tar ball.</para>
   <tip><para><application>#configure --help</application></para>
   <para><application># man make</application></para></tip>   
   </sect3>
   
   <sect3 id="bzipped">
   <title>Bzipped Tar Balls</title>
   <para>This mode of distribution uses a powerful compression method (<application> # man bzip2 </application> ) 
   that is deliberately  very similar  to gzip at the command line. It is impressive how much size and download time  can be saved using this
compression method. </para>
   <para>Installation with bzip2 is nearly identical to gnuzip.</para>
    <para>To install &app; from the same directory as the package :</para>
   <orderedlist>
   <listitem>
   	<para>
   	<emphasis>[user@ X]#</emphasis>
   	<programlisting> tar Ixvf &app;&version;.tar.bz2</programlisting>
   	</para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user@ X]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting>cd &app;&version;
   </programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user @ &app;&version]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> ./configure</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[user @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> ./make</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting>su</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> password: your-root-password</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para>
   <emphasis>[root @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting>./make install</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para><emphasis>[root @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> exit</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   <listitem>
   <para><emphasis>[user @&app;&version;]#</emphasis>
   <programlisting> cronos</programlisting>
   </para>
   </listitem>
   </orderedlist>
   </sect3>
   
   <sect3 id="rpms">
   <title>Red Hat Packages</title>
      <para>These packages are used by many LINUX distributions as a simple and
       effective way of installing software and keeping issues like dependencies in order.
       Other distributions have their own equally useful approaches that achieve similar ends.</para>
       <para> Installation may be undertaken from the command line,or a  GUI front end to RPM
       like <application>GNORPM</application> . 
       In all cases root level permissions are required to install system wide.
       </para>
       <para>At the command line do the following as ROOT  from the same directory as you have the package. :</para>
       <orderedlist>
       <listitem>
       <para><emphasis>[root@x]#</emphasis>
       <programlisting>
       <application>rpm -Uvh &app;&version</application>
       </programlisting>
       </para>
       </listitem>
       <listitem>
       <para>
       <emphasis>[root@x]#</emphasis>
       <programlisting><application>exit</application></programlisting></para>
       <para> or<programlisting><application> login </application></programlisting>
       to your normal account
       </para>
       </listitem>
       <listitem><para><emphasis>[user@x]#</emphasis><programlisting><application> cronos</application></programlisting></para></listitem>
       </orderedlist>
  		<tip><para>As &app; tarballs include a <emphasis>spec </emphasis> file you may build your own <application>RPM</application>
  		 by typing the following from the command line:</para><para>  (as  root) <emphasis>[root@x]#</emphasis>
  		 <programlisting>rpm -ta &app;&version;.tar.gz</programlisting></para>
  		 <para> This should (all going well) build a package ready for you to install as a standard
  		 <application>RPM</application> as shown<link linkend="rpms"> above.</link></para></tip>   
       </sect3>
       </sect2>
       </sect1>
       
       
       
